# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: spatial-transcriptomics
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:spatial-transcriptomics/fluorescence-in-situ-hybridization] FISH can also be used to detect and localize specific RNA targets (mRNA, lncRNA, and miRNA) in cells, circulating tumor cells, and tissue samples.
[src:spatial-transcriptomics/fluorescence-in-situ-hybridization] In this context, it helps define the spatial and temporal patterns of gene expression within cells and tissues.
[src:spatial-transcriptomics/fluorescence-in-situ-hybridization] In biology, a probe is a single strand of DNA or RNA that is complementary to a nucleotide sequence of interest.
[src:spatial-transcriptomics/fluorescence-in-situ-hybridization] RNA probes can be designed for any gene or any sequence within a gene for visualization of mRNA, lncRNA and miRNA in tissues and cells.
[src:spatial-transcriptomics/fluorescence-in-situ-hybridization] FISH is used by examining the cellular reproduction cycle, specifically interphase of the nuclei for any chromosomal abnormalities.
[src:spatial-transcriptomics/fluorescence-in-situ-hybridization] FISH allows the analysis of a large series of archival cases much easier to identify the pinpointed chromosome by creating a probe with an artificial chromosomal foundation that will attract similar chromosomes.
[src:spatial-transcriptomics/fluorescence-in-situ-hybridization] The hybridization signals for each probe when a nucleic abnormality is detected.
[src:spatial-transcriptomics/fluorescence-in-situ-hybridization] Each probe for the detection of mRNA and lncRNA is composed of ~20-50 oligonucleotide pairs, each pair covering a space of 40–50 bp.
[src:spatial-transcriptomics/fluorescence-in-situ-hybridization] The specifics depend on the specific FISH technique used.
[src:spatial-transcriptomics/fluorescence-in-situ-hybridization] For miRNA detection, the probes use proprietary chemistry for specific detection of miRNA and cover the entire miRNA sequence.
[src:spatial-transcriptomics/fluorescence-in-situ-hybridization] Probes are often derived from fragments of DNA that were isolated, purified, and amplified for use in the Human Genome Project.
[src:spatial-transcriptomics/fluorescence-in-situ-hybridization] The size of the human genome is so large, compared to the length that could be sequenced directly, that it was necessary to divide the genome into fragments.
[src:spatial-transcriptomics/fluorescence-in-situ-hybridization] Clonal populations of bacteria, each population maintaining a single artificial chromosome, are stored in various laboratories around the world.
[src:spatial-transcriptomics/fluorescence-in-situ-hybridization] The artificial chromosomes (BAC) can be grown, extracted, and labeled, in any lab containing a library.
[src:spatial-transcriptomics/fluorescence-in-situ-hybridization] Genomic libraries are often named after the institution in which they were developed.
[src:spatial-transcriptomics/fluorescence-in-situ-hybridization] An example being the RPCI-11 library, which is named after Roswell Park Comprehensive Cancer Center (formerly known as Roswell Park Cancer Institute) in Buffalo, New York.
[src:spatial-transcriptomics/fluorescence-in-situ-hybridization] These fragments are on the order of 100 thousand base-pairs, and are the basis for most FISH probes.
[src:spatial-transcriptomics/fluorescence-in-situ-hybridization] The purpose of using RNA FISH is to detect target mRNA transcripts in cells, tissue sections, or even whole-mounts.
[src:spatial-transcriptomics/fluorescence-in-situ-hybridization] The process is done in 3 main procedures: tissue preparation (pre-hybridization), hybridization, and washing (post-hybridization).
[src:spatial-transcriptomics/fluorescence-in-situ-hybridization] The tissue preparation starts by collecting the appropriate tissue sections to perform RNA FISH.
[src:spatial-transcriptomics/fluorescence-in-situ-hybridization] First, cells, circulating tumor cells (CTCs), formalin-fixed paraffin-embedded (FFPE), or frozen tissue sections are "fixed." Fixing involves treating live cells with a chemical fixative like 4% formaldehyde or paraformaldehyde (PFA) in phosphate buffered saline (PBS).
[src:spatial-transcriptomics/fluorescence-in-situ-hybridization] This fixative process essentially "preserves" the structural integrity of the cells prior to permeabilization of the cell membrane which is normally conducted with a detergent like triton-X, which is pertinent for cell staining as dead cells no longer have a functioning membrane.
[src:spatial-transcriptomics/fluorescence-in-situ-hybridization] Cell permeabilization can also be done using a 70% ethanol solution and overnight refrigeration.
[src:spatial-transcriptomics/fluorescence-in-situ-hybridization] However, FISH has also been successfully done on unfixed cells.
[src:spatial-transcriptomics/fluorescence-in-situ-hybridization] After fixation, samples are permeabilized to allow the penetration of hybridization reagents.
[src:spatial-transcriptomics/fluorescence-in-situ-hybridization] The use of detergents at a 0.1% concentration is commonly used to enhance the tissue permeability such as Tween-20 or Triton X-100.
[src:spatial-transcriptomics/fluorescence-in-situ-hybridization] It is critical for the hybridization process to have all optimal conditions to have a successful in situ result, including temperature, pH, salt concentration, and time of the hybridization reaction.
[src:spatial-transcriptomics/fluorescence-in-situ-hybridization] After checking all the necessary conditions, hybridization steps can be started by first adding a target-specific probe, composed of 20 oligonucleotide pairs, hybridizes to the target RNA(s).
[src:spatial-transcriptomics/fluorescence-in-situ-hybridization] Separate but compatible signal amplification systems enable the multiplex assay (up to two targets per assay).
[src:spatial-transcriptomics/fluorescence-in-situ-hybridization] Signal amplification is achieved via series of sequential hybridization steps.
[src:spatial-transcriptomics/fluorescence-in-situ-hybridization] After the hybridization steps, washing steps are performed.
[src:spatial-transcriptomics/fluorescence-in-situ-hybridization] These steps aim to remove nonspecific hybrids and get rid of unbound probe molecules from the samples to reduce any background signaling.
[src:spatial-transcriptomics/fluorescence-in-situ-hybridization] The use of ethanol washes are typically used at this stage to reduce autofluorescence in tissues or cells.
[src:spatial-transcriptomics/fluorescence-in-situ-hybridization] At the end of the assay the tissue samples are visualized under a fluorescence microscope such as the confocal fluorescence microscope and the Keyence microscope.
[src:spatial-transcriptomics/fluorescence-in-situ-hybridization] The probe must be large enough to hybridize specifically with its target but not so large as to impede the hybridization process.
[src:spatial-transcriptomics/fluorescence-in-situ-hybridization] The probe is tagged directly with fluorophores, with targets for antibodies or with biotin.
[src:spatial-transcriptomics/fluorescence-in-situ-hybridization] Tagging can be done in various ways, such as nick translation, or polymerase chain reaction using tagged nucleotides.
[src:spatial-transcriptomics/fluorescence-in-situ-hybridization] Then, an interphase or metaphase chromosome preparation is produced.
[src:spatial-transcriptomics/fluorescence-in-situ-hybridization] The chromosomes are firmly attached to a substrate, usually glass.
[src:spatial-transcriptomics/fluorescence-in-situ-hybridization] Repetitive DNA sequences must be blocked by adding short fragments of DNA to the sample.
[src:spatial-transcriptomics/fluorescence-in-situ-hybridization] The probe is then applied to the chromosome DNA and incubated for approximately 12 hours while hybridizing.
[src:spatial-transcriptomics/fluorescence-in-situ-hybridization] Several wash steps remove all unhybridized or partially hybridized probes.
[src:spatial-transcriptomics/fluorescence-in-situ-hybridization] The results are then visualized and quantified using a microscope that is capable of exciting the dye and recording images.
[src:spatial-transcriptomics/fluorescence-in-situ-hybridization] If the fluorescent signal is weak, amplification of the signal may be necessary in order to exceed the detection threshold of the microscope.
[src:spatial-transcriptomics/fluorescence-in-situ-hybridization] Fluorescent signal strength depends on many factors such as probe labeling efficiency, the type of probe, and the type of dye.
[src:spatial-transcriptomics/fluorescence-in-situ-hybridization] Fluorescently tagged antibodies or streptavidin are bound to the dye molecule.
[src:spatial-transcriptomics/fluorescence-in-situ-hybridization] These secondary components are selected so that they have a strong signal.
[src:spatial-transcriptomics/fluorescence-in-situ-hybridization] The differences between the various FISH techniques are usually due to variations in the sequence and labeling of the probes; and how they are used in combination.
[src:spatial-transcriptomics/fluorescence-in-situ-hybridization] Probes are divided into two generic categories: cellular and acellular.
[src:spatial-transcriptomics/fluorescence-in-situ-hybridization] In fluorescent "in situ" hybridization refers to the cellular placement of the probe.
[src:spatial-transcriptomics/fluorescence-in-situ-hybridization] Probe size is important because shorter probes hybridize less specifically than longer probes, so that long enough strands of DNA or RNA (often 10–25 nucleotides) which are complementary to a given target sequence are often used to locate a target.
[src:spatial-transcriptomics/fluorescence-in-situ-hybridization] The overlap defines the resolution of detectable features.
[src:spatial-transcriptomics/fluorescence-in-situ-hybridization] For example, if the goal of an experiment is to detect the breakpoint of a translocation, then the overlap of the probes — the degree to which one DNA sequence is contained in the adjacent probes — defines the minimum window in which the breakpoint may be detected.
[src:spatial-transcriptomics/fluorescence-in-situ-hybridization] The mixture of probe sequences determines the type of feature the probe can detect.
[src:spatial-transcriptomics/fluorescence-in-situ-hybridization] Probes that hybridize along an entire chromosome are used to count the number of a certain chromosome, show translocations, or identify extra-chromosomal fragments of chromatin.
[src:spatial-transcriptomics/fluorescence-in-situ-hybridization] This is often called "whole-chromosome painting." If every possible probe is used, every chromosome, (the whole genome) would be marked fluorescently, which would not be particularly useful for determining features of individual sequences.
[src:spatial-transcriptomics/fluorescence-in-situ-hybridization] However, it is possible to create a mixture of smaller probes that are specific to a particular region (locus) of DNA; these mixtures are used to detect deletion mutations.
[src:spatial-transcriptomics/fluorescence-in-situ-hybridization] When combined with a specific color, a locus-specific probe mixture is used to detect very specific translocations.
[src:spatial-transcriptomics/fluorescence-in-situ-hybridization] A variety of other techniques uses mixtures of differently colored probes.
[src:spatial-transcriptomics/fluorescence-in-situ-hybridization] A range of colors in mixtures of fluorescent dyes can be detected, so each human chromosome can be identified by a characteristic color using whole-chromosome probe mixtures and a variety of ratios of colors.
[src:spatial-transcriptomics/fluorescence-in-situ-hybridization] Although there are more chromosomes than easily distinguishable fluorescent dye colors, ratios of probe mixtures can be used to create *secondary* colors.
[src:spatial-transcriptomics/fluorescence-in-situ-hybridization] Similar to comparative genomic hybridization, the probe mixture for the secondary colors is created by mixing the correct ratio of two sets of differently colored probes for the same chromosome.
[src:spatial-transcriptomics/fluorescence-in-situ-hybridization] This technique is sometimes called M-FISH.
[src:spatial-transcriptomics/fluorescence-in-situ-hybridization] The same physics that make a variety of colors possible for M-FISH can be used for the detection of translocations.
[src:spatial-transcriptomics/fluorescence-in-situ-hybridization] That is, colors that are adjacent appear to overlap; a secondary color is observed.
[src:spatial-transcriptomics/fluorescence-in-situ-hybridization] Some assays are designed so that the secondary color will be present or absent in cases of interest.
[src:spatial-transcriptomics/fluorescence-in-situ-hybridization] An example is the detection of BCR/ABL translocations, where the secondary color indicates disease.
[src:spatial-transcriptomics/fluorescence-in-situ-hybridization] This variation is often called double-fusion FISH or D-FISH.
[src:spatial-transcriptomics/fluorescence-in-situ-hybridization] In the opposite situation—where the absence of the secondary color is pathological—is illustrated by an assay used to investigate translocations where only one of the breakpoints is known or constant.
[src:spatial-transcriptomics/fluorescence-in-situ-hybridization] Locus-specific probes are made for one side of the breakpoint and the other intact chromosome.
[src:spatial-transcriptomics/fluorescence-in-situ-hybridization] In normal cells, the secondary color is observed, but only the primary colors are observed when the translocation occurs.
[src:spatial-transcriptomics/fluorescence-in-situ-hybridization] This technique is sometimes called "break-apart FISH".
[src:spatial-transcriptomics/fluorescence-in-situ-hybridization] Single-molecule RNA FISH, also known as Stellaris® RNA FISH or smFISH, is a method of detecting and quantifying mRNA and other long RNA molecules in a thin layer of tissue sample.
[src:spatial-transcriptomics/fluorescence-in-situ-hybridization] Targets can be reliably imaged through the application of multiple short singly labeled oligonucleotide probes.
[src:spatial-transcriptomics/fluorescence-in-situ-hybridization] The binding of up to 48 fluorescent labeled oligos to a single molecule of mRNA provides sufficient fluorescence to accurately detect and localize each target mRNA in a wide-field fluorescent microscopy image.
[src:spatial-transcriptomics/fluorescence-in-situ-hybridization] Probes not binding to the intended sequence do not achieve sufficient localized fluorescence to be distinguished from background.
[src:spatial-transcriptomics/fluorescence-in-situ-hybridization] Single-molecule RNA FISH assays can be performed in simplex or multiplex, and can be used as a follow-up experiment to quantitative PCR, or imaged simultaneously with a fluorescent antibody assay.
[src:spatial-transcriptomics/fluorescence-in-situ-hybridization] The technology has potential applications in cancer diagnosis, neuroscience, gene expression analysis, and companion diagnostics.
[src:spatial-transcriptomics/fluorescence-in-situ-hybridization] This is accomplished by applying mechanical shear along the length of the slide, either to cells that have been fixed to the slide and then lysed, or to a solution of purified DNA.
[src:spatial-transcriptomics/fluorescence-in-situ-hybridization] A technique known as chromosome combing is increasingly used for this purpose.
[src:spatial-transcriptomics/fluorescence-in-situ-hybridization] The extended conformation of the chromosomes allows dramatically higher resolution – even down to a few kilobases.
[src:spatial-transcriptomics/fluorescence-in-situ-hybridization] The preparation of fiber FISH samples, although conceptually simple, is a rather skilled art, and only specialized laboratories use the technique routinely.
[src:spatial-transcriptomics/fluorescence-in-situ-hybridization] Q-FISH combines FISH with PNAs and computer software to quantify fluorescence intensity.
[src:spatial-transcriptomics/fluorescence-in-situ-hybridization] This technique is used routinely in telomere length research.
[src:spatial-transcriptomics/fluorescence-in-situ-hybridization] Flow-FISH uses flow cytometry to perform FISH automatically using per-cell fluorescence measurements.
[src:spatial-transcriptomics/fluorescence-in-situ-hybridization] Microfluidics-assisted FISH (MA-FISH) uses a microfluidic flow to increase DNA hybridization efficiency, decreasing expensive FISH probe consumption and reduce the hybridization time.
[src:spatial-transcriptomics/fluorescence-in-situ-hybridization] MA-FISH is applied for detecting the *HER2* gene in breast cancer tissues.
[src:spatial-transcriptomics/fluorescence-in-situ-hybridization] Microautoradiography FISH is a technique to combine radio-labeled substrates with conventional FISH to detect phylogenetic groups and metabolic activities simultaneously.
[src:spatial-transcriptomics/fluorescence-in-situ-hybridization] Hybrid Fusion FISH (HF-FISH) uses primary additive excitation/emission combination of fluorophores to generate additional spectra through a labeling process known as dynamic optical transmission (DOT).
[src:spatial-transcriptomics/fluorescence-in-situ-hybridization] Three primary fluorophores are able to generate a total of 7 readily detectable emission spectra as a result of combinatorial labeling using DOT.
[src:spatial-transcriptomics/fluorescence-in-situ-hybridization] Hybrid Fusion FISH enables highly multiplexed FISH applications that are targeted within clinical oncology panels.
[src:spatial-transcriptomics/fluorescence-in-situ-hybridization] The technology offers faster scoring with efficient probesets that can be readily detected with traditional fluorescent microscopes.
[src:spatial-transcriptomics/fluorescence-in-situ-hybridization] Multiplexed error-robust fluorescence in situ hybridization is a highly multiplexed version of smFISH.
[src:spatial-transcriptomics/fluorescence-in-situ-hybridization] It uses combinatorial labeling, followed by imaging, and then error-resistant encoding to capture a high number of RNA molecules and spatial localization within the cell.
[src:spatial-transcriptomics/fluorescence-in-situ-hybridization] The capture of a large number of RNA molecules enables elucidation of gene regulatory networks, prediction of function of unannotated genes, and identification of RNA molecule distribution patterns, which correlate with their associated proteins.
[src:spatial-transcriptomics/fluorescence-in-situ-hybridization] Starfish is a set of software tools developed in 2019 by a consortium of scientists to analyze data from nine different variations of FISH, since all variations produce the same set of data—gene expression values mapped to x and y coordinates in a cell.
[src:spatial-transcriptomics/fluorescence-in-situ-hybridization] The software, created for all scientists, not just bioinformaticians, reads a set of images, removes noise, and identifies RNA molecules.
[src:spatial-transcriptomics/fluorescence-in-situ-hybridization] This approach has set out to define a standard analysis scheme of FISH datasets in a similar way to single-cell transcriptomics analysis.
[src:spatial-transcriptomics/fluorescence-in-situ-hybridization] Often parents of children with a developmental disability want to know more about their child's conditions before choosing to have another child.
[src:spatial-transcriptomics/fluorescence-in-situ-hybridization] These concerns can be addressed by analysis of the parents' and child's DNA.
[src:spatial-transcriptomics/fluorescence-in-situ-hybridization] In cases where the child's developmental disability is not understood, the cause of it can potentially be determined using FISH and cytogenetic techniques.
[src:spatial-transcriptomics/fluorescence-in-situ-hybridization] Examples of diseases that are diagnosed using FISH include Prader-Willi syndrome, Angelman syndrome, 22q13 deletion syndrome, chronic myelogenous leukemia, acute lymphoblastic leukemia, Cri-du-chat, Velocardiofacial syndrome, and Down syndrome.
[src:spatial-transcriptomics/fluorescence-in-situ-hybridization] FISH on sperm cells is indicated for men with an abnormal somatic or meiotic karyotype as well as those with oligozoospermia, since approximately 50% of oligozoospermic men have an increased rate of sperm chromosome abnormalities.
[src:spatial-transcriptomics/fluorescence-in-situ-hybridization] The analysis of chromosomes 21, X, and Y is enough to identify oligozoospermic individuals at risk.
[src:spatial-transcriptomics/fluorescence-in-situ-hybridization] In medicine, FISH can be used to form a diagnosis, to evaluate prognosis, or to evaluate remission of a disease, such as cancer.
[src:spatial-transcriptomics/fluorescence-in-situ-hybridization] Treatment can then be specifically tailored.
[src:spatial-transcriptomics/fluorescence-in-situ-hybridization] A traditional exam involving metaphase chromosome analysis is often unable to identify features that distinguish one disease from another, due to subtle chromosomal features; FISH can elucidate these differences.
[src:spatial-transcriptomics/fluorescence-in-situ-hybridization] FISH can also be used to detect diseased cells more easily than standard Cytogenetic methods, which require dividing cells and requires labor and time-intensive manual preparation and analysis of the slides by a technologist.
[src:spatial-transcriptomics/fluorescence-in-situ-hybridization] FISH, on the other hand, does not require living cells and can be quantified automatically, a computer counts the fluorescent dots present.
[src:spatial-transcriptomics/fluorescence-in-situ-hybridization] However, a trained technologist is required to distinguish subtle differences in banding patterns on bent and twisted metaphase chromosomes.
[src:spatial-transcriptomics/fluorescence-in-situ-hybridization] FISH can be incorporated into Lab-on-a-chip microfluidic device.
[src:spatial-transcriptomics/fluorescence-in-situ-hybridization] This technology is still in a developmental stage but, like other lab on a chip methods, it may lead to more portable diagnostic techniques.
[src:spatial-transcriptomics/fluorescence-in-situ-hybridization] FISH has been extensively studied as a diagnostic technique for the identification of pathogens in the field of medical microbiology.
[src:spatial-transcriptomics/fluorescence-in-situ-hybridization] Although it has been proven to be a useful and applicable technique, it is still not widely applied in diagnostic laboratories.
[src:spatial-transcriptomics/fluorescence-in-situ-hybridization] The short time to diagnosis (less than 2 hours) has been a major advantage compared with biochemical differentiation, but this advantage is challenged by MALDI-TOF-MS which allows the identification of a wider range of pathogens compared with biochemical differentiation techniques.
[src:spatial-transcriptomics/fluorescence-in-situ-hybridization] Using FISH for diagnostic purposes has found its purpose when immediate species identification is needed, specifically for the investigation of blood cultures for which FISH is a cheap and easy technique for preliminary rapid diagnosis.
[src:spatial-transcriptomics/fluorescence-in-situ-hybridization] FISH can also be used to compare the genomes of two biological species, to deduce evolutionary relationships.
[src:spatial-transcriptomics/fluorescence-in-situ-hybridization] A similar hybridization technique is called a zoo blot.
[src:spatial-transcriptomics/fluorescence-in-situ-hybridization] Bacterial FISH probes are often primers for the 16s rRNA region.
[src:spatial-transcriptomics/fluorescence-in-situ-hybridization] FISH is widely used in the field of microbial ecology, to identify microorganisms.
[src:spatial-transcriptomics/fluorescence-in-situ-hybridization] Biofilms, for example, are composed of complex (often) multi-species bacterial organizations.
[src:spatial-transcriptomics/fluorescence-in-situ-hybridization] Preparing DNA probes for one species and performing FISH with this probe allows one to visualize the distribution of this specific species within the biofilm.
[src:spatial-transcriptomics/fluorescence-in-situ-hybridization] Preparing probes (in two different colors) for two species allows researchers to visualize/study co-localization of these two species in the biofilm and can be useful in determining the fine architecture of the biofilm.
[src:spatial-transcriptomics/fluorescence-in-situ-hybridization] Comparative genomic hybridization can be described as a method that uses FISH in a parallel manner with the comparison of the hybridization strength to recall any major disruptions in the duplication process of the DNA sequences in the genome of the nucleus.
[src:spatial-transcriptomics/fluorescence-in-situ-hybridization] Spectral karyotyping is an image of colored chromosomes.
[src:spatial-transcriptomics/fluorescence-in-situ-hybridization] Spectral karyotyping involves FISH using multiple forms of many types of probes with the result to see each chromosome labeled through its metaphase stage.
[src:spatial-transcriptomics/fluorescence-in-situ-hybridization] This type of karyotyping is used specifically when seeking out chromosome arrangements.
[src:spatial-transcriptomics/fluorescence-in-situ-hybridization] Virtual karyotyping is another cost-effective, clinically available alternative to FISH panels using thousands to millions of probes on a single array to detect copy number changes, genome-wide, at unprecedented resolution.
[src:spatial-transcriptomics/fluorescence-in-situ-hybridization] Currently, this type of analysis will only detect gains and losses of chromosomal material and will not detect balanced rearrangements, such as translocations and inversions which are hallmark aberrations seen in many types of leukemia and lymphoma.
[src:spatial-transcriptomics/fluorescence-in-situ-hybridization] FISH can be used to study the evolution of chromosomes.
[src:spatial-transcriptomics/fluorescence-in-situ-hybridization] Species that are related have similar chromosomes.
[src:spatial-transcriptomics/fluorescence-in-situ-hybridization] This homology can be detected by gene or genome sequencing but also by FISH.
[src:spatial-transcriptomics/fluorescence-in-situ-hybridization] For instance, human and chimpanzee chromosomes are very similar, and FISH can demonstrate that the common ancestor of chimpanzees and humans had two smaller chromosomes, and in the human lineage these fused to result in one human chromosome.
[src:spatial-transcriptomics/fluorescence-in-situ-hybridization] Similarly, species that are more distantly related, have similar chromosomes but with increasing genetic distance, chromosomes tend to break and fuse and thus result in mosaic chromosomes.
[src:spatial-transcriptomics/fluorescence-in-situ-hybridization] This can be impressively demonstrated by FISH (see figure).
[src:spatial-transcriptomics/immunohistochemistry] Immunohistochemical staining is widely used in the diagnosis of abnormal cells such as those found in cancerous tumors.
[src:spatial-transcriptomics/immunohistochemistry] In some cancer cells certain tumor antigens are expressed which make it possible to detect.
[src:spatial-transcriptomics/immunohistochemistry] Immunohistochemistry is also widely used in basic research, to understand the distribution and localization of biomarkers and differentially expressed proteins in different parts of a biological tissue.
[src:spatial-transcriptomics/immunohistochemistry] Immunohistochemistry can be performed on tissue that has been fixed and embedded in paraffin, but also cryopreservated (frozen) tissue.
[src:spatial-transcriptomics/immunohistochemistry] Based on the way the tissue is preserved, there are different steps to prepare the tissue for immunohistochemistry, but the general method includes proper fixation, antigen retrieval, incubation with primary antibody, then incubation with secondary antibody.
[src:spatial-transcriptomics/immunohistochemistry] Fixation of the tissue is important to preserve the tissue and maintaining cellular morphology.
[src:spatial-transcriptomics/immunohistochemistry] The fixation formula, ratio of fixative to tissue and time in the fixative, will affect the result.
[src:spatial-transcriptomics/immunohistochemistry] The fixation solution (fixative) is often 10% neutral buffer formalin.
[src:spatial-transcriptomics/immunohistochemistry] Normal fixation time is 24 hours in room temperature.
[src:spatial-transcriptomics/immunohistochemistry] The ratio of fixative to tissue ranges from 1:1 to 1:20.
[src:spatial-transcriptomics/immunohistochemistry] After the tissue is fixed it can be embedded in paraffin wax.
[src:spatial-transcriptomics/immunohistochemistry] For frozen sections, fixation is usually performed after sectioning if not new antibodies are going to be tested.
[src:spatial-transcriptomics/immunohistochemistry] Sectioning of the tissue sample is done using a microtome.
[src:spatial-transcriptomics/immunohistochemistry] For paraffin embedded tissue 4 μm is normal thickness, and for frozen sections 4 – 6 μm.
[src:spatial-transcriptomics/immunohistochemistry] The thickness of the sliced sections matters, and is an important factor in immunohistochemistry.
[src:spatial-transcriptomics/immunohistochemistry] If you compare a section of brain tissue measuring 4 μm with a section measuring 7 μm, some of what you see in the 7 μm thick section might be lacking in the 4 μm section.
[src:spatial-transcriptomics/immunohistochemistry] This shows the importance of detailed methods related to this methodology.
[src:spatial-transcriptomics/immunohistochemistry] The paraffin embedded tissues should be deparaffinized to remove all the paraffin on and around the tissue sample in xylene or a good substitute, followed by alcohol.
[src:spatial-transcriptomics/immunohistochemistry] Antigen retrieval is required to make the epitopes accessible for immunohistochemical staining for most formalin fixed tissue section.
[src:spatial-transcriptomics/immunohistochemistry] The epitopes are the binding sites for antibodies used to visualize the targeted antigen which may be masked due to the fixation.
[src:spatial-transcriptomics/immunohistochemistry] Fixation of the tissue may cause formation of methylene bridges or crosslinking of amino groups, so that the epitopes no longer are available.
[src:spatial-transcriptomics/immunohistochemistry] Antigen retrieval can restore the masked antigenicity, possibly by breaking down the crosslinks caused by fixation.
[src:spatial-transcriptomics/immunohistochemistry] The most common way to perform antigen retrieval is by using high-temperature heating while soaking the slides in a buffer solution.
[src:spatial-transcriptomics/immunohistochemistry] This can be done in different ways, for example by using microwave oven, autoclaves, heating plates or water baths.
[src:spatial-transcriptomics/immunohistochemistry] For frozen sections, antigen retrieval is generally not necessary, but for frozen sections that have been fixed in acetone or formalin, antigen retrieval can improve the immunohistochemical signal.
[src:spatial-transcriptomics/immunohistochemistry] Non-specific binding of antibodies can cause background staining.
[src:spatial-transcriptomics/immunohistochemistry] Although antibodies bind to specific epitopes, they may also partially or weakly bind to sites on nonspecific proteins that are similar to the binding site on the target protein.
[src:spatial-transcriptomics/immunohistochemistry] By incubating the tissue with normal serum isolated from the species which the secondary antibody was produced, the background staining can be reduced.
[src:spatial-transcriptomics/immunohistochemistry] It is also possible to use commercially available universal blocking buffers.
[src:spatial-transcriptomics/immunohistochemistry] Other common blocking buffers include normal serum, non-fat dry milk, BSA, or gelatin.
[src:spatial-transcriptomics/immunohistochemistry] Endogenous enzyme activity may also cause background staining but can be reduced if the tissue is treated with hydrogen peroxide.
[src:spatial-transcriptomics/immunohistochemistry] After preparing the sample, the target can be visualized by using antibodies labeled with fluorescent compounds, metals or enzymes.
[src:spatial-transcriptomics/immunohistochemistry] There are direct and indirect methods for labeling the sample.
[src:spatial-transcriptomics/immunohistochemistry] The antibodies used for detection can be polyclonal or monoclonal.
[src:spatial-transcriptomics/immunohistochemistry] Polyclonal antibodies are made by using animals like guinea pig, rabbit, mouse, rat, or goat.
[src:spatial-transcriptomics/immunohistochemistry] The animal is injected with the antigen of interest and trigger an immune response.
[src:spatial-transcriptomics/immunohistochemistry] The antibodies can be isolated from the animal's whole serum.
[src:spatial-transcriptomics/immunohistochemistry] Polyclonal antibody production will result in a mixture of different antibodies and will recognize multiple epitopes.
[src:spatial-transcriptomics/immunohistochemistry] Monoclonal antibodies are made by injecting the animal with the antigen of interest and then isolating an antibody-producing B cell, typically from the spleen.
[src:spatial-transcriptomics/immunohistochemistry] The antibody producing cell is then fused with a cancer cell line.
[src:spatial-transcriptomics/immunohistochemistry] This causes the antibodies to show specificity for a single epitope.
[src:spatial-transcriptomics/immunohistochemistry] For immunohistochemical detection strategies, antibodies are classified as primary or secondary reagents.
[src:spatial-transcriptomics/immunohistochemistry] Primary antibodies are raised against an antigen of interest and are typically unconjugated (unlabeled).
[src:spatial-transcriptomics/immunohistochemistry] Secondary antibodies are raised against immunoglobulins of the primary antibody species.
[src:spatial-transcriptomics/immunohistochemistry] The secondary antibody is usually conjugated to a linker molecule, such as biotin, that then recruits reporter molecules, or the secondary antibody itself is directly bound to the reporter molecule.
[src:spatial-transcriptomics/immunohistochemistry] The direct method is a one-step staining method and involves a labeled antibody reacting directly with the antigen in tissue sections.
[src:spatial-transcriptomics/immunohistochemistry] While this technique utilizes only one antibody and therefore is simple and rapid, the sensitivity is lower due to little signal amplification, in contrast to indirect approaches.
[src:spatial-transcriptomics/immunohistochemistry] The indirect method involves an unlabeled primary antibody that binds to the target antigen in the tissue.
[src:spatial-transcriptomics/immunohistochemistry] Then a secondary antibody, which binds with the primary antibody is added as a second layer.
[src:spatial-transcriptomics/immunohistochemistry] As mentioned, the secondary antibody must be raised against the antibody IgG of the animal species in which the primary antibody has been raised.
[src:spatial-transcriptomics/immunohistochemistry] This method is more sensitive than direct detection strategies because of signal amplification due to the binding of several secondary antibodies to each primary antibody.
[src:spatial-transcriptomics/immunohistochemistry] The indirect method, aside from its greater sensitivity, also has the advantage that only a relatively small number of standard conjugated (labeled) secondary antibodies needs to be generated.
[src:spatial-transcriptomics/immunohistochemistry] For example, a labeled secondary antibody raised against rabbit IgG, is useful with any primary antibody raised in rabbit.
[src:spatial-transcriptomics/immunohistochemistry] This is particularly useful when a researcher is labeling more than one primary antibody, whether due to polyclonal selection producing an array of primary antibodies for a singular antigen or when there is interest in multiple antigens.
[src:spatial-transcriptomics/immunohistochemistry] With the direct method, it would be necessary to label each primary antibody for every antigen of interest.
[src:spatial-transcriptomics/immunohistochemistry] Reporter molecules vary based on the nature of the detection method, the most common being chromogenic and fluorescence detection.
[src:spatial-transcriptomics/immunohistochemistry] In chromogenic immunohistochemistry an antibody is conjugated to an enzyme, such as alkaline phosphate and horseradish peroxidase, that can catalyze a color-producing reaction in the presence of a chromogenic substrate like 3,3'-diaminobenzidine (DAB).
[src:spatial-transcriptomics/immunohistochemistry] The colored product can be analyzed with an ordinary light microscope.
[src:spatial-transcriptomics/immunohistochemistry] In immunofluorescence the antibody is tagged to a fluorophore, such as fluorescein isothiocyanate, tetramethylrhodamine isothiocyanate, aminomethyl Coumarin acetate or Cyanine5.
[src:spatial-transcriptomics/immunohistochemistry] Synthetic fluorochromes from Alexa Fluors is also commonly used.
[src:spatial-transcriptomics/immunohistochemistry] The fluorochromes can be visualized by a fluorescence or confocal microscope.
[src:spatial-transcriptomics/immunohistochemistry] For chromogenic and fluorescent detection methods, densitometric analysis of the signal can provide semi- and fully quantitative data, respectively, to correlate the level of reporter signal to the level of protein expression or localization.
[src:spatial-transcriptomics/immunohistochemistry] After immunohistochemical staining of the target antigen, another stain is often applied.
[src:spatial-transcriptomics/immunohistochemistry] The counterstain provide contrast that helps the primary stain stand out and makes it easier to examine the tissue morphology.
[src:spatial-transcriptomics/immunohistochemistry] It also helps with orientation and visualization of the tissue section.
[src:spatial-transcriptomics/immunohistochemistry] In immunohistochemical techniques, there are several steps prior to the final staining of the tissue that can cause a variety of problems.
[src:spatial-transcriptomics/immunohistochemistry] It can be strong background staining, weak target antigen staining and presence of artifacts.
[src:spatial-transcriptomics/immunohistochemistry] It is important that antibody quality and the immunohistochemistry techniques are optimized.
[src:spatial-transcriptomics/immunohistochemistry] Endogenous biotin, reporter enzymes or primary/secondary antibody cross-reactivity are common causes of strong background staining.
[src:spatial-transcriptomics/immunohistochemistry] Weak or absent staining may be caused by inaccurate fixation of the tissue or to low antigen levels.
[src:spatial-transcriptomics/immunohistochemistry] These aspects of immunohistochemistry tissue prep and antibody staining must be systematically addressed to identify and overcome staining issues.
[src:spatial-transcriptomics/immunohistochemistry] Methods to eliminate background staining include dilution of the primary or secondary antibodies, changing the time or temperature of incubation, and using a different detection system or different primary antibody.
[src:spatial-transcriptomics/immunohistochemistry] Immunohistochemistry is an excellent detection technique and has the tremendous advantage of being able to show exactly where a given protein is located within the tissue examined.
[src:spatial-transcriptomics/immunohistochemistry] It is also an effective way to examine the tissues.
[src:spatial-transcriptomics/immunohistochemistry] This has made it a widely used technique in neuroscience, enabling researchers to examine protein expression within specific brain structures.
[src:spatial-transcriptomics/immunohistochemistry] Its major disadvantage is that, unlike immunoblotting techniques where staining is checked against a molecular weight ladder, it is impossible to show in immunohistochemistry that the staining corresponds with the protein of interest.
[src:spatial-transcriptomics/immunohistochemistry] For this reason, primary antibodies must be well-validated in a Western Blot or similar procedure.
[src:spatial-transcriptomics/immunohistochemistry] The technique is even more widely used in diagnostic surgical pathology for immunophenotyping tumors (e.g. immunostaining for e-cadherin to differentiate between ductal carcinoma in situ (stains positive) and lobular carcinoma in situ (does not stain positive)).
[src:spatial-transcriptomics/immunohistochemistry] More recently, immunohistochemical techniques have been useful in differential diagnoses of multiple forms of salivary gland, head, and neck carcinomas.
[src:spatial-transcriptomics/immunohistochemistry] The diversity of immunohistochemistry markers used in diagnostic surgical pathology is substantial.
[src:spatial-transcriptomics/immunohistochemistry] Many clinical laboratories in tertiary hospitals will have menus of over 200 antibodies used as diagnostic, prognostic and predictive biomarkers.
[src:spatial-transcriptomics/immunohistochemistry] A variety of molecular pathways are altered in cancer and some of the alterations can be targeted in cancer therapy.
[src:spatial-transcriptomics/immunohistochemistry] Immunohistochemistry can be used to assess which tumors are likely to respond to therapy, by detecting the presence or elevated levels of the molecular target.
[src:spatial-transcriptomics/immunohistochemistry] Tumor biology allows for a number of potential intracellular targets.
[src:spatial-transcriptomics/immunohistochemistry] The presence of hormone receptors can be used to determine if a tumor is potentially responsive to antihormonal therapy.
[src:spatial-transcriptomics/immunohistochemistry] One of the first therapies was the antiestrogen, tamoxifen, used to treat breast cancer.
[src:spatial-transcriptomics/immunohistochemistry] Such hormone receptors can be detected by immunohistochemistry.
[src:spatial-transcriptomics/immunohistochemistry] Imatinib, an intracellular tyrosine kinase inhibitor, was developed to treat chronic myelogenous leukemia, a disease characterized by the formation of a specific abnormal tyrosine kinase.
[src:spatial-transcriptomics/immunohistochemistry] Imitanib has proven effective in tumors that express other tyrosine kinases, most notably KIT.
[src:spatial-transcriptomics/immunohistochemistry] Most gastrointestinal stromal tumors express KIT, which can be detected by immunohistochemistry.
[src:spatial-transcriptomics/immunohistochemistry] Many proteins shown to be highly upregulated in pathological states by immunohistochemistry are potential targets for therapies utilising monoclonal antibodies.
[src:spatial-transcriptomics/immunohistochemistry] Monoclonal antibodies, due to their size, are utilized against cell surface targets.
[src:spatial-transcriptomics/immunohistochemistry] Among the overexpressed targets are members of the EGFR family, transmembrane proteins with an extracellular receptor domain regulating an intracellular tyrosine kinase.
[src:spatial-transcriptomics/immunohistochemistry] Of these, HER2/neu (also known as Erb-B2) was the first to be developed.
[src:spatial-transcriptomics/immunohistochemistry] The molecule is highly expressed in a variety of cancer cell types, most notably breast cancer.
[src:spatial-transcriptomics/immunohistochemistry] As such, antibodies against HER2/neu have been FDA approved for clinical treatment of cancer under the drug name *Herceptin*.
[src:spatial-transcriptomics/immunohistochemistry] There are commercially available immunohistochemical tests, Dako HercepTest, Leica Biosystems Oracle and Ventana Pathway.
[src:spatial-transcriptomics/immunohistochemistry] Similarly, epidermal growth factor receptor (HER-1) is overexpressed in a variety of cancers including head and neck and colon.
[src:spatial-transcriptomics/immunohistochemistry] Immunohistochemistry is used to determine patients who may benefit from therapeutic antibodies such as Erbitux (cetuximab).
[src:spatial-transcriptomics/immunohistochemistry] Commercial systems to detect epidermal growth factor receptor by immunohistochemistry include the Dako pharmDx.
[src:spatial-transcriptomics/immunohistochemistry] Immunohistochemistry can also be used for a more general protein profiling, provided the availability of antibodies validated for immunohistochemistry.
[src:spatial-transcriptomics/immunohistochemistry] The Human Protein Atlas displays a map of protein expression in normal human organs and tissues.
[src:spatial-transcriptomics/immunohistochemistry] The combination of immunohistochemistry and tissue microarrays provides protein expression patterns in a large number of different tissue types.
[src:spatial-transcriptomics/immunohistochemistry] Immunohistochemistry is also used for protein profiling in the most common forms of human cancer.
[src:spatial-transcriptomics/in-situ-hybridization] In situ hybridization is used to reveal the location of specific nucleic acid sequences on chromosomes or in tissues, a crucial step for understanding the organization, regulation, and function of genes.
[src:spatial-transcriptomics/in-situ-hybridization] DNA ISH can be used to determine the structure of chromosomes.
[src:spatial-transcriptomics/in-situ-hybridization] Fluorescent DNA ISH (FISH) can, for example, be used in medical diagnostics to assess chromosomal integrity.
[src:spatial-transcriptomics/in-situ-hybridization] RNA ISH (RNA *in situ* hybridization) is used to measure and localize RNAs (mRNAs, lncRNAs, and miRNAs) within tissue sections, cells, whole mounts, and circulating tumor cells (CTCs).
[src:spatial-transcriptomics/in-situ-hybridization] *In situ* hybridization was invented by American biologists Mary-Lou Pardue and Joseph G.
[src:spatial-transcriptomics/in-situ-hybridization] In situ hybridization is a powerful technique for identifying specific mRNA species within individual cells in tissue sections, providing insights into physiological processes and disease pathogenesis.
[src:spatial-transcriptomics/in-situ-hybridization] However, in situ hybridization requires that many steps be taken with precise optimization for each tissue examined and for each probe used.
[src:spatial-transcriptomics/in-situ-hybridization] In order to preserve the target mRNA within tissues, it is often required that crosslinking fixatives (such as formaldehyde) be used.
[src:spatial-transcriptomics/in-situ-hybridization] In addition, in-situ hybridization on tissue sections require that tissue slices be very thin, usually 3 μm to 7 μm in thickness.
[src:spatial-transcriptomics/in-situ-hybridization] Common methods of preparing tissue sections for in-situ hybridization processing include cutting specimens with a cryostat or a Compresstome tissue slicer.
[src:spatial-transcriptomics/in-situ-hybridization] A cryostat takes fresh or fixed tissue and immerses it into liquid nitrogen for flash freezing.
[src:spatial-transcriptomics/in-situ-hybridization] Then tissue is embedded in freeze media called OCT and thin sections are cut.
[src:spatial-transcriptomics/in-situ-hybridization] Obstacles include getting freeze artifacts on tissue that may interfere with proper mRNA staining.
[src:spatial-transcriptomics/in-situ-hybridization] The Compresstome cuts tissue into thin slices without a freeze process; free-floating sections are cut after being embedded in agarose for stability.
[src:spatial-transcriptomics/in-situ-hybridization] This method avoids freezing tissue and thus associated freeze artifacts.
[src:spatial-transcriptomics/in-situ-hybridization] The process is permanent and irreversible once its complete.
[src:spatial-transcriptomics/in-situ-hybridization] For hybridization histochemistry, sample cells and tissues are usually treated to fix the target transcripts in place and to increase access of the probe.
[src:spatial-transcriptomics/in-situ-hybridization] As noted above, the probe is either a labeled complementary DNA or, now most commonly, a complementary RNA (riboprobe).
[src:spatial-transcriptomics/in-situ-hybridization] The probe hybridizes to the target sequence at elevated temperature, and then the excess probe is washed away (after prior hydrolysis using RNase in the case of unhybridized, excess RNA probe).
[src:spatial-transcriptomics/in-situ-hybridization] Solution parameters such as temperature, salt, and/or detergent concentration can be manipulated to remove any non-identical interactions (i.e., only exact sequence matches will remain bound).
[src:spatial-transcriptomics/in-situ-hybridization] Then, the probe that was labeled with either radio-, fluorescent- or antigen-labeled bases (e.g., digoxigenin) is localized and quantified in the tissue using either autoradiography, fluorescence microscopy, or immunohistochemistry, respectively.
[src:spatial-transcriptomics/in-situ-hybridization] ISH can also use two or more probes, labeled with radioactivity or the other non-radioactive labels, to simultaneously detect two or more transcripts.
[src:spatial-transcriptomics/in-situ-hybridization] An alternative technology, branched DNA assay, can be used for RNA (mRNA, lncRNA, and miRNA ) *in situ* hybridization assays with single molecule sensitivity without the use of radioactivity.
[src:spatial-transcriptomics/in-situ-hybridization] This approach (e.g., ViewRNA assays) can be used to visualize up to four targets in one assay, and it uses patented probe design and bDNA signal amplification to generate sensitive and specific signals.
[src:spatial-transcriptomics/in-situ-hybridization] Samples (cells, tissues, and CTCs) are fixed, then treated to allow RNA target accessibility (RNA un-masking).
[src:spatial-transcriptomics/in-situ-hybridization] Target-specific probes hybridize to each target RNA.
[src:spatial-transcriptomics/in-situ-hybridization] Subsequent signal amplification is predicated on specific hybridization of adjacent probes (individual oligonucleotides [oligos] that bind side by side on RNA targets).
[src:spatial-transcriptomics/in-situ-hybridization] A typical target-specific probe will contain 40 oligonucleotides, resulting in 20 oligo pairs that bind side-by-side on the target for detection of mRNA and lncRNA, and 2 oligos or a single pair for miRNA detection.
[src:spatial-transcriptomics/in-situ-hybridization] Signal amplification is achieved via a series of sequential hybridization steps.
[src:spatial-transcriptomics/in-situ-hybridization] A pre-amplifier molecule hybridizes to each oligo pair on the target-specific RNA, then multiple amplifier molecules hybridize to each pre-amplifier.
[src:spatial-transcriptomics/in-situ-hybridization] Next, multiple label probe oligonucleotides (conjugated to alkaline phosphatase or directly to fluorophores) hybridize to each amplifier molecule.
[src:spatial-transcriptomics/in-situ-hybridization] A fully assembled signal amplification structure “Tree” has 400 binding sites for the label probes.
[src:spatial-transcriptomics/in-situ-hybridization] When all target-specific probes bind to the target mRNA transcript, an 8,000 fold signal amplification occurs for that one transcript.
[src:spatial-transcriptomics/in-situ-hybridization] Separate but compatible signal amplification systems enable the multiplex assays.
[src:spatial-transcriptomics/in-situ-hybridization] The signal can be visualized using a fluorescence or brightfield microscope.
[src:spatial-transcriptomics/in-situ-hybridization] The protocol takes around 2–3 days and takes some time to set up.
[src:spatial-transcriptomics/in-situ-hybridization] Some companies sell robots to automate the process (e.g., CEM InsituPro).
[src:spatial-transcriptomics/in-situ-hybridization] As a result, large-scale screenings have been conducted in laboratories on thousands of genes.
[src:spatial-transcriptomics/in-situ-hybridization] The results can usually be accessed via websites (see external links).
[src:spatial-transcriptomics/laser-capture-microdissection] Laser-capture microdissection (LCM) is a method to procure subpopulations of tissue cells under direct microscopic visualization.
[src:spatial-transcriptomics/laser-capture-microdissection] LCM technology can harvest the cells of interest directly or can isolate specific cells by cutting away unwanted cells to give histologically pure enriched cell populations.
[src:spatial-transcriptomics/laser-capture-microdissection] A variety of downstream applications exist: DNA genotyping and loss of heterozygosity (LOH) analysis, RNA transcript profiling, cDNA library generation, proteomics discovery and signal-pathway profiling.
[src:spatial-transcriptomics/laser-capture-microdissection] The total time required to carry out this protocol is typically 1–1.5 h.
[src:spatial-transcriptomics/laser-capture-microdissection] A laser is coupled into a microscope and focuses onto the tissue on the slide.
[src:spatial-transcriptomics/laser-capture-microdissection] By movement of the laser by optics or the stage the focus follows a trajectory which is predefined by the user.
[src:spatial-transcriptomics/laser-capture-microdissection] This trajectory, also called *element*, is then cut out and separated from the adjacent tissue.
[src:spatial-transcriptomics/laser-capture-microdissection] After the cutting process, an extraction process has to follow if an extraction process is desired.
[src:spatial-transcriptomics/laser-capture-microdissection] More recent technologies utilize non-contact microdissection.
[src:spatial-transcriptomics/laser-capture-microdissection] There are several ways to extract tissue from a microscope slide with a histopathology sample on it.
[src:spatial-transcriptomics/laser-capture-microdissection] Press a sticky surface onto the sample and tear out.
[src:spatial-transcriptomics/laser-capture-microdissection] This extracts the desired region, but can also remove particles or unwanted tissue on the surface, because the surface is not selective.
[src:spatial-transcriptomics/laser-capture-microdissection] Melt a plastic membrane onto the sample and tear out.
[src:spatial-transcriptomics/laser-capture-microdissection] The heat is introduced, for example, by a red or infrared (IR) laser onto a membrane stained with an absorbing dye.
[src:spatial-transcriptomics/laser-capture-microdissection] As this adheres the desired sample onto the membrane, as with any membrane that is put close to the histopathology sample surface, there might be some debris extracted.
[src:spatial-transcriptomics/laser-capture-microdissection] Another danger is the introduced heat: Some molecules like DNA, RNA, or protein don't allow to be heated too much or at all for the goal of being isolated as purely as possible.
[src:spatial-transcriptomics/laser-capture-microdissection] Transport by gravity using an upright microscope (called GAM, gravity-assisted microdissection) or transport by *laser pressure catapult*; the most recent generation utilizes a technology based on laser induced forward transfer (LIFT).
[src:spatial-transcriptomics/laser-capture-microdissection] With cut-and-capture, a cap coated with an adhesive is positioned directly on the thinly cut (5-8 μm) tissue section, the section itself resting on a thin membrane (polyethylene naphthalene).
[src:spatial-transcriptomics/laser-capture-microdissection] An IR laser gently heats the adhesive on the cap fusing it to the underlying tissue and an UV laser cuts through tissue and underlying membrane.
[src:spatial-transcriptomics/laser-capture-microdissection] The membrane-tissue entity now adheres to the cap and the cells on the cap can be used in downstream applications (DNA, RNA, protein analysis).
[src:spatial-transcriptomics/laser-capture-microdissection] Currently six primary isolation/collection technologies exist using a microscope and device for cell isolation.
[src:spatial-transcriptomics/laser-capture-microdissection] Four of these typically use an ultraviolet pulsed laser (355 nm) for the cutting of the tissues directly or the membranes/film, and sometimes in combination with an IR laser responsible for heating/melting a sticky polymer for cellular adhesion and isolation.
[src:spatial-transcriptomics/laser-capture-microdissection] IR laser provides a more gentle approach to microdissection.
[src:spatial-transcriptomics/laser-capture-microdissection] A fifth ultraviolet laser based technology uses special slides coated with an energy transfer coating which, when activated by the laser pulse, propels the tissue or cells into a collection cap.
[src:spatial-transcriptomics/laser-capture-microdissection] The laser cutting width is usually less than 1 μm, thus the target cells are not affected by the laser beam.
[src:spatial-transcriptomics/laser-capture-microdissection] Even live cells are not damaged by the laser cutting and are viable after cutting for cloning and reculturing as appropriate.
[src:spatial-transcriptomics/laser-capture-microdissection] The various technologies differ in the collection process, possible imaging methods (fluorescence microscopy/bright field microscopy/differential interference contrast microscopy/phase contrast microscopy/ etc.) and the types of holders and tissue preparation needed before the imaging and isolation.
[src:spatial-transcriptomics/laser-capture-microdissection] Most are primarily dedicated micro-dissection systems, and some can be used as research microscopes as well, only one technology (#2 here, Leica) uses an upright microscope, limiting some of the sample handling capabilities somewhat, especially for live cell work.
[src:spatial-transcriptomics/laser-capture-microdissection] The first technology (used by Carl Zeiss PALM) cuts around the sample then collects it by a "catapulting" technology.
[src:spatial-transcriptomics/laser-capture-microdissection] The sample can be catapulted from a slide or special culture dish by a defocused U.V laser pulse which generates a photonic force to propel the material off the slide/dish, a technique sometimes called Laser Micro-dissection Pressure Catapulting (LMPC).
[src:spatial-transcriptomics/laser-capture-microdissection] The dissected material is sent upward (up to several millimetres) to a microfuge tube cap or other collector which contains either a buffer or a specialized tacky material in the tube cap that the tissue will adhere to.
[src:spatial-transcriptomics/laser-capture-microdissection] This active catapulting process avoids some of the static problems when using membrane-coated slides.
[src:spatial-transcriptomics/laser-capture-microdissection] Another process follows gravity-assisted microdissection method that turns on gravity to collect samples in tube cap under the slide used (used by ION LMD system, Jungwoo F&B).
[src:spatial-transcriptomics/laser-capture-microdissection] In case of this system, it moves the motorized stage to cut the cells of interests, keeping the laser beam fixed.
[src:spatial-transcriptomics/laser-capture-microdissection] And the system uses a 355 nm Solid-state laser(UV-A) which is the safest way to cut the tissues without RNA or DNA damage.
[src:spatial-transcriptomics/laser-capture-microdissection] Another closely related LCM process (used by Leica) cuts the sample from above and the sample drops via gravity (gravity-assisted microdissection) into a capture device below the sample.
[src:spatial-transcriptomics/laser-capture-microdissection] The different point with upper one is, the laser beam here is moving to cut tissue by moving dichroic mirror.
[src:spatial-transcriptomics/laser-capture-microdissection] When the cells (on a slide or special culture dish) of choice are in the center of the field of view, the operator selects the cells of interest using instrument software.
[src:spatial-transcriptomics/laser-capture-microdissection] The area to be isolated when a near-IR laser to activate transfer film on a cap placed on the tissue sample, melting the adhesive which then fuses the film with the underlying cells of choice (see Arcturus systems); and/or by activating a UV laser to cut out the cell of interest.
[src:spatial-transcriptomics/laser-capture-microdissection] The cells are then lifted off the thin tissue section, leaving all unwanted cells behind.
[src:spatial-transcriptomics/laser-capture-microdissection] The cells of interest are then viewed and documented prior to extraction.
[src:spatial-transcriptomics/laser-capture-microdissection] A fifth UV based technology uses standard glass slides coated with an inert energy transfer coating and a UV based laser microdissection system (typically a Leica LMD or PALM Zeiss machine).
[src:spatial-transcriptomics/laser-capture-microdissection] Tissue sections are mounted on top of the energy transfer coating.
[src:spatial-transcriptomics/laser-capture-microdissection] The energy from a UV laser is converted to kinetic energy upon striking the coating, vaporizing it, instantly propelling selected tissue features into the collection tube.
[src:spatial-transcriptomics/laser-capture-microdissection] The energy transfer coated slides, commercialized under the trade name DIRECTOR slides by Expression Pathology Inc.
[src:spatial-transcriptomics/laser-capture-microdissection] (Rockville, MD), offer several advantages for proteomic work.
[src:spatial-transcriptomics/laser-capture-microdissection] They also do not autofluoresce, so they can be used for applications using fluorescent stains, DIC or polarized light.
[src:spatial-transcriptomics/laser-capture-microdissection] In addition to tissue sections, LCM can be performed on living cells/organisms, cell smears, chromosome preparations, and plant tissue.
[src:spatial-transcriptomics/laser-capture-microdissection] The laser capture microdissection process does not alter or damage the morphology and chemistry of the sample collected, nor the surrounding cells.
[src:spatial-transcriptomics/laser-capture-microdissection] For this reason, LCM is a useful method of collecting selected cells for DNA, RNA and/or protein analyses.
[src:spatial-transcriptomics/laser-capture-microdissection] LCM has also been used to isolate acellular structures, such as amyloid plaques.
[src:spatial-transcriptomics/laser-capture-microdissection] LCM can be performed on a variety of tissue samples including blood smears, cytologic preparations, cell cultures and aliquots of solid tissue.
[src:spatial-transcriptomics/laser-capture-microdissection] Frozen and paraffin embedded archival tissue may also be used.
[src:spatial-transcriptomics/laser-capture-microdissection] As of 2025, there are two major providers of laser-assisted microdissection systems: Leica Microsystems and MMI.
[src:spatial-transcriptomics/laser-capture-microdissection] Formerly significant providers Zeiss and Arcturus have discontinued their respective systems.
[src:spatial-transcriptomics/laser-capture-microdissection] The LMD system couples an upright microscope with a UV laser.
[src:spatial-transcriptomics/laser-capture-microdissection] Using Laser Microbeam Microdissection (LMD), specific regions of a tissue section, down to single cells or chromosomes — can be excised without contact using a pulsed UV laser.
[src:spatial-transcriptomics/laser-capture-microdissection] A focused laser beam is guided along the contours of the selected areas.
[src:spatial-transcriptomics/laser-capture-microdissection] In the Leica LMD system, the dissected material is transported contact-free into a collector by gravity.
[src:spatial-transcriptomics/laser-capture-microdissection] Various consumables can be used as slide carriers depending on the intended application.
[src:spatial-transcriptomics/laser-capture-microdissection] The laser microdissection technology used by Molecular Machines and Industries GmbH (MMI), designed for use with inverted microscopes, is based on a UV laser.
[src:spatial-transcriptomics/laser-capture-microdissection] Sample preparation involves a "sandwich method," where the sample is positioned between an inert membrane slide and a glass slide.
[src:spatial-transcriptomics/laser-capture-microdissection] The UV laser precisely cuts out the target area.
[src:spatial-transcriptomics/laser-capture-microdissection] The isolated sample, along with the membrane, is then lifted by an "adhesive cap" — a sticky lid of the reaction vessel.
[src:spatial-transcriptomics/laser-capture-microdissection] Since the sample never comes into contact with the adhesive cap due to the sandwich structure, contamination-free sample collection is ensured.
[src:spatial-transcriptomics/laser-capture-microdissection] The MMI system supports fully automated sample isolation, which can be performed either with adhesive caps or directly into a 96-well plate.
[src:spatial-transcriptomics/laser-capture-microdissection] The technology is suitable for single-cell analysis.
[src:spatial-transcriptomics/laser-capture-microdissection] AI-assisted software can identify individual cells on the slide and then automatically isolate them via laser microdissection.
[src:spatial-transcriptomics/laser-capture-microdissection] A comparative study from 2024 examined the collection efficiency of the MMI system versus Leica Microsystems' gravity-based system.
[src:spatial-transcriptomics/laser-capture-microdissection] The MMI system demonstrated a sample recovery efficiency of 100%, whereas the Leica system showed more frequent sample losses.
[src:spatial-transcriptomics/spatial-transcriptomics] Spatial transcriptomics includes methods that can be divided into two modalities, those based in next-generation sequencing for gene detection, and those based in imaging.
[src:spatial-transcriptomics/spatial-transcriptomics] Some common approaches to resolve spatial distribution of transcripts are microdissection techniques, fluorescent *in situ* hybridization methods, *in situ* sequencing, *in situ* capture protocols and *in silico* approaches.
[src:spatial-transcriptomics/spatial-transcriptomics] Doyle and his co-investigators described a method called Spatial Analysis of Genomic Activity (SAGA).
[src:spatial-transcriptomics/spatial-transcriptomics] This spatial indexing concept was expanded upon in 2016 by Jonas Frisén, Joakim Lundeberg, Patrik Ståhl and their colleagues in Stockholm, Sweden.
[src:spatial-transcriptomics/spatial-transcriptomics] In 2019, the first commercial platforms for spatial transcriptomics were launched with GeoMx Digital Spatial Profiler (DSP) by Nanostring Technologies and Visium by 10X Genomics.
[src:spatial-transcriptomics/spatial-transcriptomics] In 2019, at the Broad Institute, the labs of Fei Chen and Evan Macosko developed Slide-seq, which used barcoded oligos on beads.
[src:spatial-transcriptomics/spatial-transcriptomics] Defining the spatial distribution of mRNA molecules allows for the detection of cellular heterogeneity in tissues, tumours, and immune cells as well as determining the subcellular distribution of transcripts in various conditions.
[src:spatial-transcriptomics/spatial-transcriptomics] This information provides a unique opportunity to decipher both the cellular and subcellular architecture in both tissues and individual cells.
[src:spatial-transcriptomics/spatial-transcriptomics] These methodologies provide crucial insights in the fields of embryology, oncology, immunology, neuroscience, pathology, and histology.
[src:spatial-transcriptomics/spatial-transcriptomics] The functioning of the individual cells in multicellular organisms can only be completely explained in the context of identifying their exact location in the body.
[src:spatial-transcriptomics/spatial-transcriptomics] Spatial transcriptomics techniques sought to elucidate cells' properties this way.
[src:spatial-transcriptomics/spatial-transcriptomics] Below, we look into the methods that connect gene expression to the spatial organization of cells.
[src:spatial-transcriptomics/spatial-transcriptomics] Laser capture microdissection enables capturing single cells without causing morphologic alterations.
[src:spatial-transcriptomics/spatial-transcriptomics] It exploits transparent ethylene vinyl acetate film apposed to the histological section and a low-power infrared laser beam.
[src:spatial-transcriptomics/spatial-transcriptomics] Once such beam is directed at the cells of interest, film directly above the targeted area temporarily melts so that its long-chain polymers cover and tightly capture the cells.
[src:spatial-transcriptomics/spatial-transcriptomics] Then, the section is removed and cells of interest remain embedded in the film.
[src:spatial-transcriptomics/spatial-transcriptomics] This method allows further RNA transcript profiling and cDNA library generation of the retrieved cells.
[src:spatial-transcriptomics/spatial-transcriptomics] RNA sequencing of the selected regions in individual cryosections is another method that can produce location-based genome-wide expression data.
[src:spatial-transcriptomics/spatial-transcriptomics] This method is carried out without laser capture microdissection.
[src:spatial-transcriptomics/spatial-transcriptomics] It was first used to determine genome-wide spatial patterns of gene expression in cryo-sliced Drosophila embryos.
[src:spatial-transcriptomics/spatial-transcriptomics] Essentially, it implies simple preparation of the library from the selected regions of the sample.
[src:spatial-transcriptomics/spatial-transcriptomics] This method had difficulties in obtaining high-quality RNA-seq libraries from every section due to the material loss as a result of the small amount of total RNA in each slice.
[src:spatial-transcriptomics/spatial-transcriptomics] This problem was resolved by adding RNA of a distantly related Drosophila species to each tube after initial RNA extraction.
[src:spatial-transcriptomics/spatial-transcriptomics] The GeoMx Digital Spatial Profiler (DSP) (NanoString Technologies) is the first automated commercial instrument developed for spatial profiling of RNAs and proteins in archival formalin-fixed, paraffin-embedded (FFPE) tissue sections.
[src:spatial-transcriptomics/spatial-transcriptomics] FFPE is a common sample type in the field of pathology and histology due to its long term preservation of tissue structure.
[src:spatial-transcriptomics/spatial-transcriptomics] The GeoMx DSP technology centers around a user's ability to perform "microdissection" based on histological structures, functional compartments, and cell types.
[src:spatial-transcriptomics/spatial-transcriptomics] However, unlike LCM, gene expression profiling is performed in a nondestructive manner through light, due to a UV-photocleavable barcode engineered into the *in situ* hybridization probe.
[src:spatial-transcriptomics/spatial-transcriptomics] To do this, tissue sections on microscope slides are stained with fluorescent antibodies and nuclear dye to visualize the whole tissue section at single cell resolution on the DSP instrument.
[src:spatial-transcriptomics/spatial-transcriptomics] Selection of region of interests occurs through automated segmentation on flurorescent signal intensities or drawing tools, including geometric or free hand shapes.
[src:spatial-transcriptomics/spatial-transcriptomics] Each region of interest is precisely exposed to UV light and the barcodes are cleaved, collected, and used to identify RNAs or proteins present in the tissue.
[src:spatial-transcriptomics/spatial-transcriptomics] The defined regions of interest can vary in size, between ten and six hundred micrometers, allowing a wide variety of structures and cells in the histological sample.
[src:spatial-transcriptomics/spatial-transcriptomics] GeoMx DSP can spatially resolve and measure human or mouse whole transcriptomes, more than 1200 proteins, or both RNA and protein in multiomic same slide protocols.
[src:spatial-transcriptomics/spatial-transcriptomics] Transcriptome in vivo analysis (TIVA) is a technique that enables capturing mRNA in live single cells in intact live tissue sections.
[src:spatial-transcriptomics/spatial-transcriptomics] The TIVA tag has several functional groups and a trapped poly(U) oligonucleotide coupled to biotin.
[src:spatial-transcriptomics/spatial-transcriptomics] A disulfide-linked peptide, which is adjacent to the tag, allows it to penetrate the cell membrane.
[src:spatial-transcriptomics/spatial-transcriptomics] Once inside, laser photoactivation is used to unblock poly(U) oligonucleotide in the cells of interest, so that TIVA tag hybridizes to mRNAs within the cell.
[src:spatial-transcriptomics/spatial-transcriptomics] Then, streptavidin capture of the biotin group is used to extract poly(A)-tailed mRNA molecules bound to unblocked tags, after which these mRNAs are analyzed by RNA sequencing.
[src:spatial-transcriptomics/spatial-transcriptomics] This method is limited by low throughput, as only a few single cells can be processed at a time.
[src:spatial-transcriptomics/spatial-transcriptomics] An advanced alternative for RNA Sequencing of Individual Cryosections described above, RNA tomography (tomo-seq) features better RNA quantification and spatial resolution.
[src:spatial-transcriptomics/spatial-transcriptomics] It is also based on tissue cryosectioning with further RNA sequencing of individual sections, yielding genome-wide expression data and preserving spatial information.
[src:spatial-transcriptomics/spatial-transcriptomics] In this protocol, usage of carrier RNA is omitted due to linear amplification of cDNA in individual histological sections.
[src:spatial-transcriptomics/spatial-transcriptomics] The identical sample is sectioned in different directions followed by 3D transcriptional construction using overlapping data.
[src:spatial-transcriptomics/spatial-transcriptomics] Overall, this method implies using identical samples for each section and thus cannot be applied for processing clinical material.
[src:spatial-transcriptomics/spatial-transcriptomics] LCM-seq utilizes laser capture microdissection (LCM) coupled with Smart-Seq2 RNA sequencing and is applicable down to the single cell level and can even be used on partially degraded tissues.
[src:spatial-transcriptomics/spatial-transcriptomics] The workflow includes cryosectioning of tissues followed by laser capture microdissection, where cells are collected directly into lysis buffer and cDNA is generated without the need for RNA isolation, which both simplifies the experimental procedures as well as lowers technical noise.
[src:spatial-transcriptomics/spatial-transcriptomics] As the positional identity of each cell is recorded during the LCM procedure, the transcriptome of each cell after RNA sequencing of the corresponding cDNA library can be inferred to the position where it was isolated from.
[src:spatial-transcriptomics/spatial-transcriptomics] LCM-seq has been applied to multiple cell types to understand their intrinsic properties, including oculomotor neurons, facial motor neurons, hypoglossal motor neurons, spinal motor neurons, red nucleus neurons, interneurons, dopamine neurons, and chondrocytes.
[src:spatial-transcriptomics/spatial-transcriptomics] Geo-seq is a method that utilizes both laser capture microdissection and single-cell RNA sequencing procedures to determine the spatial distribution of the transcriptome in tissue areas approximately ten cells in size.
[src:spatial-transcriptomics/spatial-transcriptomics] The workflow involves removal and cryosectioning of tissue followed by laser capture microdissection.
[src:spatial-transcriptomics/spatial-transcriptomics] The extracted tissue is then lysed, and the RNA is purified and reverse transcribed into a cDNA library.
[src:spatial-transcriptomics/spatial-transcriptomics] Library is sequenced, and the transcriptomic profile can be mapped to the original location of the extracted tissue.
[src:spatial-transcriptomics/spatial-transcriptomics] This technique allows the user to define regions of interest in a tissue, extract said tissue and map the transcriptome in a targeted approach.
[src:spatial-transcriptomics/spatial-transcriptomics] The NICHE-seq method uses photoactivatable fluorescent markers and two-photon laser scanning microscopy to provide spatial data to the transcriptome generated.
[src:spatial-transcriptomics/spatial-transcriptomics] The cells bound by the fluorescent marker are photoactivated, dissociated and sorted via fluorescence-activated cell sorting.
[src:spatial-transcriptomics/spatial-transcriptomics] This provides sorting specificity to only labeled, photoactivated cells.
[src:spatial-transcriptomics/spatial-transcriptomics] Following sorting, single-cell RNA sequencing generates the transcriptome of the visualized cells.
[src:spatial-transcriptomics/spatial-transcriptomics] This method can process thousands of cells within a defined niche at the cost of losing spatial data between cells in the niche.
[src:spatial-transcriptomics/spatial-transcriptomics] ProximID is a methodology based on iterative micro digestion of extracted tissue to single cells.
[src:spatial-transcriptomics/spatial-transcriptomics] Initial mild digestion steps preserve small interacting structures that are recorded prior to continued digestion.
[src:spatial-transcriptomics/spatial-transcriptomics] The single cells are then separated from each structure and undergo sc-RNAseq and clustered using t-distributed stochastic neighbour embedding.
[src:spatial-transcriptomics/spatial-transcriptomics] The clustered cells can be mapped to physical interactions based on the interacting structures prior to the micro digestions.
[src:spatial-transcriptomics/spatial-transcriptomics] While the throughput of this technique is relatively low it provides information on physical interaction between cells to the dataset.
[src:spatial-transcriptomics/spatial-transcriptomics] The CosMx Spatial Molecular Imager (NanoString Technologies) is the first high-plex *in situ* analysis platform to provide spatial multiomics with formalin-fixed paraffin-embedded (FFPE) and fresh frozen (FF) tissue samples at cellular and subcellular resolution.
[src:spatial-transcriptomics/spatial-transcriptomics] It enables rapid quantification and visualization of up to the whole transcriptome and 64 validated protein analytes and is the flexible, spatial single-cell imaging platform for cell atlasing, tissue phenotyping, cell-cell interactions, cellular processes, and biomarker discovery.
[src:spatial-transcriptomics/spatial-transcriptomics] One of the first techniques able to achieve spatially resolved RNA profiling of individual cells was single-molecule fluorescent *in situ* hybridization (smFISH).
[src:spatial-transcriptomics/spatial-transcriptomics] It implemented short (50 base pairs) oligonucleotide probes conjugated with 5 fluorophores which could bind to a specific transcript yielding bright spots in the sample.
[src:spatial-transcriptomics/spatial-transcriptomics] Detection of these spots provides quantitative information about expression of certain genes in the cell.
[src:spatial-transcriptomics/spatial-transcriptomics] However, usage of probes labeled with multiple fluorophores was challenged by self-quenching, altered hybridization characteristics, their synthesis and purification.
[src:spatial-transcriptomics/spatial-transcriptomics] Later, this method was changed by substituting the above described probes with those of 20 bp length, coupled to only one fluorophore and complementary in tandem to an mRNA sequence of interest, meaning that those would collectively bind to the targeted mRNA.
[src:spatial-transcriptomics/spatial-transcriptomics] One such probe itself wouldn't produce a strong signal, but the cumulative fluorescence of the congregated probes would show a bright spot.
[src:spatial-transcriptomics/spatial-transcriptomics] Since single misbound probes are unlikely to co-localize, false-positive signals in this method are limited.
[src:spatial-transcriptomics/spatial-transcriptomics] Thus, this *in situ* hybridization (ISH) technique spots spatial localization of RNA expression via direct imaging of individual RNA molecules in single cells.
[src:spatial-transcriptomics/spatial-transcriptomics] Another *in situ* hybridization technique termed RNAscope employs probes of the specific Z-shaped design to simultaneously amplify hybridization signals and suppress background noise.
[src:spatial-transcriptomics/spatial-transcriptomics] It allows for the visualization of single RNA in a variety of cellular types.
[src:spatial-transcriptomics/spatial-transcriptomics] Most steps of RNAScope are similar to the classic ISH protocol.
[src:spatial-transcriptomics/spatial-transcriptomics] The tissue sample is fixed onto slides and then treated with RNAscope reagents that permeate the cells.
[src:spatial-transcriptomics/spatial-transcriptomics] Z-probes are designed in a way that they are only effective when bound in pairs to the target sequence.
[src:spatial-transcriptomics/spatial-transcriptomics] This allows another element of this method (preamplifier) to connect to the top tails of Z-probes.
[src:spatial-transcriptomics/spatial-transcriptomics] Once affixed, preamplifier serves as a binding site for other elements: amplifiers which in turn bind to another type of probes: label probes.
[src:spatial-transcriptomics/spatial-transcriptomics] As a result, a bulky structure is formed on the target sequence.
[src:spatial-transcriptomics/spatial-transcriptomics] Most importantly, the preamplifier fails to bind to a singular Z-probe, thus, nonspecific binding wouldn't entail signal emission, thus, eliminating background noise mentioned in the beginning.
[src:spatial-transcriptomics/spatial-transcriptomics] Sequential fluorescence *in situ* hybridization (seqFISH) is another method that provides identification of mRNA directly in single cells with preservation of their spatial context.
[src:spatial-transcriptomics/spatial-transcriptomics] This method is carried out in multiple rounds; each of them includes fluorescent probe hybridization, imaging, and consecutive probe stripping.
[src:spatial-transcriptomics/spatial-transcriptomics] Various genes are assigned different colors in every round, generating a unique temporal barcode.
[src:spatial-transcriptomics/spatial-transcriptomics] Thus, seqFISH distinguishes mRNAs by a sequential color code, such as red-red-green.
[src:spatial-transcriptomics/spatial-transcriptomics] Nevertheless, this technique has its flaws featuring autofluorescent background and high costs due to the number of probes used in each round.
[src:spatial-transcriptomics/spatial-transcriptomics] Conventional FISH methods are limited by the small number of genes that can be simultaneously analyzed due to the small number of distinct color channels, so multiplexed error-robust FISH was designed to overcome this problem.
[src:spatial-transcriptomics/spatial-transcriptomics] Multiplexed Error-Robust FISH (MERFISH) greatly increases the number of RNA species that can be simultaneously imaged in single cells employing binary code gene labeling in multiple rounds of hybridization.
[src:spatial-transcriptomics/spatial-transcriptomics] This approach can measure 140 RNA species at a time using an encoding scheme that both detects and corrects errors.
[src:spatial-transcriptomics/spatial-transcriptomics] The core principle lies in identification of genes by combining signals from several consecutive hybridization rounds and assigning N-bit binary barcodes to genes of interest.
[src:spatial-transcriptomics/spatial-transcriptomics] The Code depends on specific probes and comprises "1" or "0" values and their combination is set differently for each gene.
[src:spatial-transcriptomics/spatial-transcriptomics] Errors are avoided by using six-bit or longer codes with any two of them differing by at least 3 bits.
[src:spatial-transcriptomics/spatial-transcriptomics] A specific probe is created for each RNA species.
[src:spatial-transcriptomics/spatial-transcriptomics] Each probe is a target-specific oligonucleotide that consists of 20-30 base pairs and complementary binds to mRNA sequence after permeating the cell.
[src:spatial-transcriptomics/spatial-transcriptomics] Then, multiple rounds of hybridization are conducted as follows: for each round, only a probe that includes "1" in the corresponding binary code position is added.
[src:spatial-transcriptomics/spatial-transcriptomics] At the end of each round, fluorescent microscopy is used to locate each probe.
[src:spatial-transcriptomics/spatial-transcriptomics] Expectedly, only those mRNAs which had "1" in the assigned position would be captured.
[src:spatial-transcriptomics/spatial-transcriptomics] Photos are then photobleached and a new subset is added.
[src:spatial-transcriptomics/spatial-transcriptomics] Thus, we retrieve combination of binary values which makes it possible to distinguish between numerous RNA species.
[src:spatial-transcriptomics/spatial-transcriptomics] Single-molecule RNA detection at depth by hybridization chain reaction (smHCR) is an advanced seqFISH technique that can overcome typical complication of autofluorescent background in thick and opaque tissue samples.
[src:spatial-transcriptomics/spatial-transcriptomics] In this method, multiple readout probes are bound with the target region of mRNA.
[src:spatial-transcriptomics/spatial-transcriptomics] Target is detected by a set of short DNA probes which attach to it in defined subsequence.
[src:spatial-transcriptomics/spatial-transcriptomics] Each DNA probe carries an initiator for the same HCR amplifier.
[src:spatial-transcriptomics/spatial-transcriptomics] Then, fluorophore-labeled DNA HCR hairpins penetrate the sample and assemble into fluorescent amplification polymers attaching to initiating probes.
[src:spatial-transcriptomics/spatial-transcriptomics] In multiplexed studies, the same two-stage protocol described above is used: all probe sets are introduced simultaneously, just as all HCR amplifiers are; spectrally distinct fluorophores are used for further imaging.
[src:spatial-transcriptomics/spatial-transcriptomics] Cyclic-ouroboros smFISH (osmFISH) is an adaptation of smFISH which aims to overcome the challenge of optical crowding.
[src:spatial-transcriptomics/spatial-transcriptomics] In osmFISH, transcripts are visualized, and an image is acquired before the probe is stripped and a new transcript is visualized with a different fluorescent probe.
[src:spatial-transcriptomics/spatial-transcriptomics] After successive rounds the images are compiled to view the spatial distribution of the RNA.
[src:spatial-transcriptomics/spatial-transcriptomics] Due to transcripts being sequentially visualized it eliminates the issue of signals interfering with each other.
[src:spatial-transcriptomics/spatial-transcriptomics] This method allows the user to generate high resolution images of larger tissue sections than other related techniques.
[src:spatial-transcriptomics/spatial-transcriptomics] Expansion FISH (ExFISH) leverages expansion microscopy to allow for super-resolution imaging of RNA location, even in thick specimens such as brain tissue.
[src:spatial-transcriptomics/spatial-transcriptomics] It supports both single-molecule and multiplexed readouts.
[src:spatial-transcriptomics/spatial-transcriptomics] Expansion-Assisted Iterative Fluorescence *In Situ* Hybridization (EASI-FISH) optimizes and builds on ExFISH with improved detection accuracy and robust multi-round processing across samples thicker (300 μm) than what was previously possible.
[src:spatial-transcriptomics/spatial-transcriptomics] It also includes a turn-key computational analysis pipeline.
[src:spatial-transcriptomics/spatial-transcriptomics] SeqFISH+ resolved optical issues related to spatial crowding by subsequent rounds of fluorescence.
[src:spatial-transcriptomics/spatial-transcriptomics] First, a primary probe anneals to targeted mRNA and then subsequent probes bind to flanking regions of the primary probe resulting in a unique barcode.
[src:spatial-transcriptomics/spatial-transcriptomics] Each readout probe is captured as an image and collapsed into a super resolved image.
[src:spatial-transcriptomics/spatial-transcriptomics] This method allows the user to target up to ten thousand genes at a time.
[src:spatial-transcriptomics/spatial-transcriptomics] DNA microscopy is a distinct imaging method for optics-free mapping of molecules' positions with simultaneous preservation of sequencing data carried out in several consecutive *in situ* reactions.
[src:spatial-transcriptomics/spatial-transcriptomics] First, cells are fixed and cDNA is synthesized.
[src:spatial-transcriptomics/spatial-transcriptomics] Randomized nucleotides then tag target cDNAs *in situ*, providing unique labels for each molecule.
[src:spatial-transcriptomics/spatial-transcriptomics] Tagged transcripts are amplified in the second *in situ* reaction, retrieved copies are concatenated, and new randomized nucleotides are added.
[src:spatial-transcriptomics/spatial-transcriptomics] Each consecutive concatenation event is labeled, yielding unique event identifiers.
[src:spatial-transcriptomics/spatial-transcriptomics] Algorithm then generates images of the original transcripts based on decoded molecular proximities from the obtained concatenated sequences, while target's single nucleotide information is being recorded as well.
[src:spatial-transcriptomics/spatial-transcriptomics] The ISS padlock method is based on padlock probing, rolling-circle amplification (RCA), and sequencing by ligation chemistry.
[src:spatial-transcriptomics/spatial-transcriptomics] Within intact tissue sections, mRNA is reversely transcribed to cDNA, which is followed by mRNA degradation by RNase H.
[src:spatial-transcriptomics/spatial-transcriptomics] Then, there are two ways of how this method can be carried out.
[src:spatial-transcriptomics/spatial-transcriptomics] The first way, gap-targeted sequencing, involves padlock probe binding to cDNA with a gap between the ends of the probe which are targeted for sequencing by ligation.
[src:spatial-transcriptomics/spatial-transcriptomics] DNA polymerization then fills this gap and a DNA circle is created by DNA ligation.
[src:spatial-transcriptomics/spatial-transcriptomics] Another way, barcode-targeted sequencing, DNA circularization of a padlock probe with a barcode sequence is conducted by ligation only.
[src:spatial-transcriptomics/spatial-transcriptomics] In both versions of the method, the ends are ligated forming a circle of DNA.
[src:spatial-transcriptomics/spatial-transcriptomics] Target amplification is then performed by RCA, yielding micrometer-sized RCA products (RCPs).
[src:spatial-transcriptomics/spatial-transcriptomics] RCAs consist of repeats of the padlock probe sequence.
[src:spatial-transcriptomics/spatial-transcriptomics] These DNA molecules are then subjected to sequencing by ligation, decoding either a gap-filled sequence or an up to four-base-long barcode within the probe with adjacent ends, depending on the version.
[src:spatial-transcriptomics/spatial-transcriptomics] No-gap variant claims higher sensitivity, while gap-filled one implies reading out the actual RNA sequence of the transcript.
[src:spatial-transcriptomics/spatial-transcriptomics] Later, this method was improved by automatization on a microfluidic platform and substitution of sequencing by ligation with sequencing by hybridization technology.
[src:spatial-transcriptomics/spatial-transcriptomics] Fluorescent *in situ* sequencing (FISSEQ), like ISS padlock, is a method that uses reverse transcription, rolling-circle amplification, and sequencing by ligation techniques.
[src:spatial-transcriptomics/spatial-transcriptomics] It allows spatial transcriptome analysis in fixed cells.
[src:spatial-transcriptomics/spatial-transcriptomics] RNA is first reverse transcribed into cDNA with regular and modified amine-bases and tagged random hexamer RT primers.
[src:spatial-transcriptomics/spatial-transcriptomics] Amine-bases mediate the cross-linkage of cDNA to its cellular surrounding.
[src:spatial-transcriptomics/spatial-transcriptomics] Then cDNA is circulated by ligation and amplified by RCA.
[src:spatial-transcriptomics/spatial-transcriptomics] Single-stranded DNA nanoballs of 200–400 nm in diameter are obtained as a result.
[src:spatial-transcriptomics/spatial-transcriptomics] Thus, these nanoballs comprise numerous tandem repeats of the cDNA sequence.
[src:spatial-transcriptomics/spatial-transcriptomics] Then sequencing is performed via SOLiD sequencing by ligation.
[src:spatial-transcriptomics/spatial-transcriptomics] Positions of both product of reverse transcription and clonally amplified RCPs are maintained via cross-linkage to cellular matrix components mentioned previously, creating a 3D *in situ* RNA-seq library within the cell.
[src:spatial-transcriptomics/spatial-transcriptomics] Once bound with fluorescent probes featuring different colors, amplicons become highly fluorescent which allows visual detection of the signal; however, the image-processing algorithm relies on read alignment to reference sequences rather than signal intensity.
[src:spatial-transcriptomics/spatial-transcriptomics] Barcode *in situ* targeted sequencing (Barista-seq) is an improvement on the gap padlock probe methodology boasting a fivefold increase in efficiency, an increased read length of fifteen bases and is compatible with illumina sequencing platforms.
[src:spatial-transcriptomics/spatial-transcriptomics] The method also uses padlock probes and rolling circle amplification, however this approach uses sequencing-by-synthesis and crosslinking unlike the gap padlock method.
[src:spatial-transcriptomics/spatial-transcriptomics] The crosslinking to the cellular matrix in the same procedure is the same as FISSEQ.
[src:spatial-transcriptomics/spatial-transcriptomics] Spatially-resolved transcript amplicon readout mapping (STARmap) utilizes a padlock probe with an additional primer which allows for direct amplification of mRNA, forgoing the need for reverse transcription.
[src:spatial-transcriptomics/spatial-transcriptomics] Similar to other padlock probe based methods amplification occurs via rolling circle amplification.
[src:spatial-transcriptomics/spatial-transcriptomics] The DNA amplicons are chemically modified and embedded into a polymerized hydrogel within the cell.
[src:spatial-transcriptomics/spatial-transcriptomics] Captured RNA can then be sequenced *in situ* providing three dimensional locations of the mRNA within each cell.
[src:spatial-transcriptomics/spatial-transcriptomics] STOmics is a pioneer in advancing spatially-resolved transcriptomic analysis through its proprietary SpaTial Enhanced REsolution Omics-Sequencing (Stereo-seq) technology.
[src:spatial-transcriptomics/spatial-transcriptomics] It combines *in situ* capture with DNB-seq, DNB sequencing is based on lithographically etched chips (patterned arrays) for *in situ* sequencing.
[src:spatial-transcriptomics/spatial-transcriptomics] Unlike other um-level *in situ* capture technologies, standard DNB chips have spots with approximately 220 nm diameter and a center-to-center distance of 500 nm, providing up to 20000 spots for tissue RNA capture per 10mm linear distance, or 4 × 108 spots per 1 cm2.
[src:spatial-transcriptomics/spatial-transcriptomics] Therefore, STOmics can show higher resolution and wider field of view than other *in situ* capture technologies.
[src:spatial-transcriptomics/spatial-transcriptomics] Frozen tissue samples are cut using cryotome, then fixed, stained, and carefully laid flat onto the microarray.
[src:spatial-transcriptomics/spatial-transcriptomics] Next, enzymatic permeabilization allows RNA molecules to diffuse to the microarray slide for hybridization of polyadenylated mRNA molecules to the oligo(dT) sequence tails.
[src:spatial-transcriptomics/spatial-transcriptomics] Reverse transcription is then carried out *in situ* for first-strand synthesis.
[src:spatial-transcriptomics/spatial-transcriptomics] As a result, spatially marked complementary DNA (cDNA) is synthesized, providing information about gene expression in the exact location of the tissue section.
[src:spatial-transcriptomics/spatial-transcriptomics] From the cDNA, libraries are generated for short-read sequencing.
[src:spatial-transcriptomics/spatial-transcriptomics] In summary, this spatial transcriptomics protocol combines paralleled sequencing and staining of the same sample.
[src:spatial-transcriptomics/spatial-transcriptomics] In the downstream analysis, bioinformatic tools allow overlay of the tissue image with the gene expression.
[src:spatial-transcriptomics/spatial-transcriptomics] The output is a map of the transcriptome captured gene expression within a tissue section.
[src:spatial-transcriptomics/spatial-transcriptomics] It is important to mention that the first generation of the arrayed slides comprised about 1,000 spots of the 100-μm diameter, limiting resolution to ~10-40 cells per spot.
[src:spatial-transcriptomics/spatial-transcriptomics] This technology was the basis of a company founded in 2012 called Spatial Transcriptomics.
[src:spatial-transcriptomics/spatial-transcriptomics] In 2018, 10X Genomics acquired Spatial Transcriptomics as the foundation for the 10X Visium platform.
[src:spatial-transcriptomics/spatial-transcriptomics] Slide-seq relies on the attachment of RNA binding, DNA-barcoded micro beads to a rubber coated glass coverslip.
[src:spatial-transcriptomics/spatial-transcriptomics] The microbeads are mapped to their spatial location via SOLiD sequencing.
[src:spatial-transcriptomics/spatial-transcriptomics] Tissue sections are transferred to this coverslip to capture extracted RNA.
[src:spatial-transcriptomics/spatial-transcriptomics] Captured RNA is amplified and sequenced.
[src:spatial-transcriptomics/spatial-transcriptomics] Transcript localization is determined by the barcode oligonucleotide sequence from the bead that captured it.
[src:spatial-transcriptomics/spatial-transcriptomics] APEX-seq allows the for assessment of the spatial transcriptome in different regions of a cell.
[src:spatial-transcriptomics/spatial-transcriptomics] The method utilizes the APEX2 gene, expressed in live cells which are incubated with biotin-phenol and hydrogen peroxide.
[src:spatial-transcriptomics/spatial-transcriptomics] In these conditions the APEX2 enzymes catalyse the transfer of biotin groups to the RNA molecules and these can then be purified via streptavidin bead purification.
[src:spatial-transcriptomics/spatial-transcriptomics] The purified transcripts are then sequenced to determine which molecules were in close proximity to the biotin tagging enzyme.
[src:spatial-transcriptomics/spatial-transcriptomics] High-Definition Spatial Transcriptomics (HDST) begins with decoding the location of mRNA capture beads in wells on a glass slide.
[src:spatial-transcriptomics/spatial-transcriptomics] This is accomplished by sequential hybridization to the barcode oligonucleotide sequence of each bead.
[src:spatial-transcriptomics/spatial-transcriptomics] Once the location of each bead is decoded, a tissue sample can be placed on the slide and permeabilized.
[src:spatial-transcriptomics/spatial-transcriptomics] The captured transcripts are then sequenced.
[src:spatial-transcriptomics/spatial-transcriptomics] HDST uses smaller beads than Slide-seq and thus can resolve at a spatial resolution of two micrometers compared to ten micrometers of Slide-seq.
[src:spatial-transcriptomics/spatial-transcriptomics] The 10X Genomics Visium assay is a newer and improved version of the Spatial Transcriptomics assay.
[src:spatial-transcriptomics/spatial-transcriptomics] It also utilizes spotted arrays of mRNA-capturing probes on the surface of glass slides but with increased spot number, minimized spot size and increased amount of capture probes per spot.
[src:spatial-transcriptomics/spatial-transcriptomics] Within each of the four capture areas of the Visium Spatial Gene Expression slides, there are approximately 5000 barcoded spots, which in turn contain millions of spatially barcoded capture oligonucleotides.
[src:spatial-transcriptomics/spatial-transcriptomics] Tissue mRNA is released upon permeabilization and binds to the barcoded oligos, enabling capture of gene expression information.
[src:spatial-transcriptomics/spatial-transcriptomics] Each barcoded spot is 55 μm in diameter, and the distance from the center of one spot to the center of another is approximately 100 μm.
[src:spatial-transcriptomics/spatial-transcriptomics] The spots are staggered to minimize the distance between them.
[src:spatial-transcriptomics/spatial-transcriptomics] On average, mRNA from anywhere between 1 and 10 cells are captured per spot which provides near single-cell resolution.
[src:spatial-transcriptomics/spatial-transcriptomics] The assay is similar in concept to the 10X Genomics Visium but has a higher density of spots.
[src:spatial-transcriptomics/spatial-transcriptomics] Contrary to the 10X Genomics Visium HD, which uses RNA probes that have to be pre-defined for species like human or mouse, SEEKER has a similar density and resolution, but will assay any fresh frozen tissue sample, using poly-A adaptation of all the mRNAs in the sample.
[src:spatial-transcriptomics/spatial-transcriptomics] Mapping the transcriptome using the Distmap algorithm requires high-throughput single cell sequencing and an existing *in situ* hybridization atlas for the tissue of interest.
[src:spatial-transcriptomics/spatial-transcriptomics] The Distmap algorithm generates a virtual 3D model of the tissue of interest using the transcriptomes of sequenced cells and said reference atlas.
[src:spatial-transcriptomics/spatial-transcriptomics] The transcriptomes can be clustered into cell types using t-distributed stochastic neighbour embedding and mapped to the 3D model using virtual *in situ* hybridization.
[src:spatial-transcriptomics/spatial-transcriptomics] Essentially, this algorithm takes data generated from single cells in a dissociated tissue and is able to map individual transcripts to where the cell type exists in the tissue using virtual *in situ* hybridization.
[src:spatial-transcriptomics/tissue-microarray] The major limitations in molecular clinical analysis of tissues include the cumbersome nature of procedures, limited availability of diagnostic reagents and limited patient sample size.
[src:spatial-transcriptomics/tissue-microarray] The technique of tissue microarray was developed to address these issues.
[src:spatial-transcriptomics/tissue-microarray] Multi-tissue blocks were first introduced by H.
[src:spatial-transcriptomics/tissue-microarray] Battifora in 1986 with his so-called "multitumor (sausage) tissue block" and modified in 1990 with its improvement, "the checkerboard tissue block" .
[src:spatial-transcriptomics/tissue-microarray] Kononen and collaborators developed the current technique, which uses a novel sampling approach to produce tissues of regular size and shape that can be more densely and precisely arrayed.
[src:spatial-transcriptomics/tissue-microarray] In the tissue microarray technique, a hollow needle is used to remove tissue cores as small as 0.6 mm in diameter from regions of interest in paraffin-embedded tissues such as clinical biopsies or tumor samples.
[src:spatial-transcriptomics/tissue-microarray] These tissue cores are then inserted in a recipient paraffin block in a precisely spaced, array pattern.
[src:spatial-transcriptomics/tissue-microarray] Sections from this block are cut using a microtome, mounted on a microscope slide and then analyzed by any method of standard histological analysis.
[src:spatial-transcriptomics/tissue-microarray] Each microarray block can be cut into 100 – 500 sections, which can be subjected to independent tests.
[src:spatial-transcriptomics/tissue-microarray] Tests commonly employed in tissue microarray include immunohistochemistry, and fluorescent in situ hybridization.
[src:spatial-transcriptomics/tissue-microarray] Tissue microarrays are particularly useful in analysis of cancer samples.
[src:spatial-transcriptomics/tissue-microarray] The use of tissue microarrays in combination with immunohistochemistry has been a preferred method to study and validate cancer biomarkers in various defined cancer patient cohorts.
[src:spatial-transcriptomics/tissue-microarray] The possibility to assemble a large number of representative cancer samples from a defined patient cohort that also has a corresponding clinical database, provides a powerful resource to study how different protein expression patterns correlate with different clinical parameters.
[src:spatial-transcriptomics/tissue-microarray] Since patient samples are assembled into the same block, sections can be stained with the same protocol to avoid experimental variability and technical artefacts.
[src:spatial-transcriptomics/tissue-microarray] Clinical cancer patient cohorts and corresponding tissue microarray sets have been used to study diagnostic, prognostic and treatment predictive cancer biomarkers in most forms of cancer, including lung, breast, colorectal and renal cell cancer.
[src:spatial-transcriptomics/tissue-microarray] Immunohistochemistry combined with tissue microarrays has also been used with success in large scale efforts to create a map of protein expression on a more global scale.
